/* CCSP :: content/quiz6.js — CCSP Domain 6 question bank (100 items). */
window.CCSP = window.CCSP || {}; CCSP.questions = CCSP.questions || [];
CCSP.questions.push.apply(CCSP.questions, [{"id":"D6-001","domain":6,"obj":"6.1","diff":"easy","q":"A U.S.-based company stores EU customer records with a cloud provider whose data centers span multiple countries. Legal counsel warns that a law-enforcement demand in one country could conflict with a data-protection statute in another. Which condition is this scenario describing?","options":["Conflicting international legislation","A gap in the SLA availability target","A failure of the shared-responsibility model","An expired audit scope statement"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Conflicting international legislation</strong> — when data crosses borders, a lawful order in one jurisdiction can directly contradict a privacy or blocking statute in another, and the organization must evaluate this legal risk before committing data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A gap in the SLA availability target</b>: availability commitments are contractual uptime, not a clash between two nations' laws.</span><span class='qd'><b>A failure of the shared-responsibility model</b>: the responsibility split addresses who secures what, not competing legal demands across borders.</span><span class='qd'><b>An expired audit scope statement</b>: audit scope defines what was examined and when, unrelated to cross-jurisdictional legal conflict.</span>"},{"id":"D6-002","domain":6,"obj":"6.1","diff":"medium","q":"During litigation, opposing counsel requests all relevant records, some of which reside in a cloud tenant. The organization must locate, preserve, and produce electronically stored information. Which ISO/IEC standard most directly guides this eDiscovery process?","options":["ISO/IEC 27017","ISO/IEC 27050","ISO/IEC 27018","ISO/IEC 27036"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>ISO/IEC 27050</strong> — this multi-part standard specifically addresses electronic discovery, covering identification, preservation, collection, processing, review, and production of ESI.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO/IEC 27017</b>: it provides cloud-specific security controls, not eDiscovery guidance.</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO/IEC 27018</b>: it covers protection of PII in public clouds, not litigation discovery.</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO/IEC 27036</b>: it addresses supplier-relationship information security, not eDiscovery.</span>"},{"id":"D6-003","domain":6,"obj":"6.1","diff":"medium","q":"A forensic investigator must acquire evidence from a virtual machine hosted by a cloud provider. Because the customer does not control the underlying hypervisor or storage, which requirement is MOST challenged compared with an on-premises acquisition?","options":["Writing the incident report","Encrypting the evidence at rest","Establishing and maintaining chain of custody","Notifying the media of the breach"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Establishing and maintaining chain of custody</strong> — in the cloud the customer lacks physical access to the media, so proving continuous, documented control of the evidence depends heavily on the provider's cooperation and processes.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Writing the incident report</b>: report writing is unaffected by whether the host is virtual or physical.</span><span class='qd'><b>Encrypting the evidence at rest</b>: encrypting a captured image is straightforward regardless of hosting model.</span><span class='qd'><b>Notifying the media of the breach</b>: media notification is a communications decision, not a forensic acquisition challenge.</span>"},{"id":"D6-004","domain":6,"obj":"6.2","diff":"easy","q":"A hospital moves patient records to a SaaS platform. Which category of data must be protected under sector-specific regulation and represents regulated (not merely contractual) private data?","options":["Marketing preferences","Publicly listed office phone numbers","Anonymous website analytics","Protected Health Information (PHI)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Protected Health Information (PHI)</strong> — PHI is regulated private data governed by statutes such as HIPAA, imposing legal obligations independent of any contract.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Marketing preferences</b>: these are typically contractual data, not regulated health information.</span><span class='qd'><b>Publicly listed office phone numbers</b>: public business contact data is generally not regulated private data.</span><span class='qd'><b>Anonymous website analytics</b>: once truly anonymized, data falls outside most privacy-regulation scope.</span>"},{"id":"D6-005","domain":6,"obj":"6.3","diff":"medium","q":"A prospective cloud customer asks the provider for an audit report it can freely share with the public on its trust website as a general seal of assurance. Which report is designed for unrestricted public distribution?","options":["SOC 3","SOC 1 Type II","SOC 2 Type II","ISAE 3402 detailed report"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>SOC 3</strong> — a SOC 3 is a short, general-use report intended for public distribution, summarizing the auditor's opinion without the detailed control descriptions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>SOC 1 Type II</b>: SOC 1 addresses controls over financial reporting and is a restricted-use report.</span><span class='qd'><b>SOC 2 Type II</b>: SOC 2 contains sensitive control detail and is restricted to informed parties under NDA.</span><span class='qd'><b>ISAE 3402 detailed report</b>: ISAE 3402 is the international analog to SOC 1 and is restricted-use.</span>"},{"id":"D6-006","domain":6,"obj":"6.3","diff":"medium","q":"An enterprise wants assurance that a cloud provider's controls for security, availability, and confidentiality were operating effectively over a six-month period. Which report BEST meets this need?","options":["SOC 1 Type I","SOC 2 Type II","SOC 2 Type I","SOC 3"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>SOC 2 Type II</strong> — SOC 2 covers the Trust Services Criteria (including security, availability, confidentiality) and a Type II report tests operating effectiveness over a period of time.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>SOC 1 Type I</b>: SOC 1 concerns financial-reporting controls, and Type I is only a point-in-time design assessment.</span><span class='qd'><b>SOC 3</b>: SOC 3 gives only a summary opinion without the detailed evidence the enterprise needs.</span><span class='qd'><b>SOC 2 Type I</b>: Type I evaluates design at a single point in time, not operating effectiveness over six months.</span>"},{"id":"D6-007","domain":6,"obj":"6.2","diff":"easy","q":"In a cloud arrangement, the customer decides what personal data is collected and why, while the provider processes that data only on the customer's documented instructions. Under most privacy frameworks, what role does the customer hold?","options":["Data processor","Data custodian","Data controller","Data subject"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Data controller</strong> — the party that determines the purposes and means of processing personal data is the controller and bears primary accountability.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Data processor</b>: the processor acts on the controller's instructions; here that is the provider, not the customer.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data custodian</b>: custodian describes operational safekeeping, not the decision-making authority over purpose.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data subject</b>: the data subject is the individual the personal data is about, not the organization.</span>"},{"id":"D6-008","domain":6,"obj":"6.3","diff":"medium","q":"A security committee is deciding how to handle a moderate residual risk that would be very costly to fully remediate in-house. They purchase a cyber-insurance policy to cover potential losses. Which risk treatment does this represent?","options":["Risk acceptance","Risk avoidance","Risk mitigation","Risk transfer"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Risk transfer</strong> — shifting the financial consequence of a risk to a third party, such as an insurer, is the definition of risk transfer.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk acceptance</b>: acceptance means bearing the loss internally without buying coverage.</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk avoidance</b>: avoidance means eliminating the activity that creates the risk, not insuring it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk mitigation</b>: mitigation reduces likelihood or impact through controls, not by shifting cost to an insurer.</span>"},{"id":"D6-009","domain":6,"obj":"6.2","diff":"medium","q":"Before deploying a new cloud analytics service that processes personal data at scale, an organization systematically assesses the effect on individuals' privacy and identifies mitigations. What is this exercise called?","options":["Privacy Impact Assessment (PIA)","Business impact analysis","Vulnerability assessment","Gap analysis"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Privacy Impact Assessment (PIA)</strong> — a PIA evaluates how a system or process affects the privacy of individuals and drives mitigations before deployment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Business impact analysis</b>: a BIA measures the operational and financial impact of disruptions, not privacy effects.</span><span class='qd'><b>Gap analysis</b>: a gap analysis compares current controls against a target standard, not privacy harm to individuals.</span><span class='qd'><b>Vulnerability assessment</b>: it identifies technical weaknesses, not privacy impacts on data subjects.</span>"},{"id":"D6-010","domain":6,"obj":"6.3","diff":"hard","q":"A cloud provider offers customers a SOC 2 report but has explicitly carved out its physical data-center operations, which are handled by a colocation subservice organization. When relying on this report, what should the customer do?","options":["Assume the carved-out controls are covered by the provider's opinion","Obtain separate assurance over the subservice organization's controls","Treat the report as invalid and reject the provider","Request a SOC 3 instead to cover the gap"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Obtain separate assurance over the subservice organization's controls</strong> — under the carve-out method those controls are excluded from the provider's report, so the customer must seek their own assurance (e.g., the colo's own SOC report) to cover the gap.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Assume the carved-out controls are covered by the provider's opinion</b>: carve-out explicitly removes them from scope, so no such coverage exists.</span><span class='qd'><b>Treat the report as invalid and reject the provider</b>: a carve-out is a legitimate, common approach, not an invalidation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Request a SOC 3 instead to cover the gap</b>: a SOC 3 is a summary of the same scope and would not add the missing subservice detail.</span>"},{"id":"D6-011","domain":6,"obj":"6.1","diff":"hard","q":"An organization operating in the EU receives a subpoena from a foreign government demanding customer data held in an EU cloud region. Producing the data could breach EU data-protection law, but refusing could violate the foreign order. What is the FIRST thing the organization should do?","options":["Immediately produce the data to satisfy the foreign court","Delete the data to avoid liability","Consult legal counsel to evaluate the conflict of laws and blocking statutes","Move the data to a third country"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Consult legal counsel to evaluate the conflict of laws and blocking statutes</strong> — when two jurisdictions' demands collide, competent legal analysis of applicable blocking statutes and treaties (e.g., MLATs) must precede any action.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Immediately produce the data to satisfy the foreign court</b>: acting before legal review could breach EU law and create liability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Delete the data to avoid liability</b>: destroying data under legal demand risks spoliation and obstruction charges.</span><span class='qd'><b>Move the data to a third country</b>: relocating data to dodge an order can itself be unlawful and worsen the conflict.</span>"},{"id":"D6-012","domain":6,"obj":"6.3","diff":"medium","q":"During cloud contract negotiation, a customer insists on a clause allowing it (or its designated auditor) to examine the provider's controls under agreed conditions. Which contractual provision is this?","options":["Termination for convenience","Escrow arrangement","Force majeure clause","Right-to-audit clause"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Right-to-audit clause</strong> — this provision grants the customer or its representative the contractual ability to inspect and verify the provider's controls.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Termination for convenience</b>: this lets a party exit the contract, not audit controls.</span><span class='qd'><b>Escrow arrangement</b>: escrow safeguards source code or assets against provider failure, not audit rights.</span><span class='qd'><b>Force majeure clause</b>: force majeure excuses performance during extraordinary events, unrelated to auditing.</span>"},{"id":"D6-013","domain":6,"obj":"6.2","diff":"medium","q":"A multinational retailer must comply with a regulation granting EU residents rights such as access, rectification, erasure, and data portability, and requiring a lawful basis for processing. Which regulation is described?","options":["GDPR","HIPAA","GLBA","SOX"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>GDPR</strong> — the General Data Protection Regulation grants EU data subjects these rights and mandates a lawful basis for processing personal data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>HIPAA</b>: HIPAA governs U.S. health information, not EU-wide personal-data rights.</span><span class='qd'><b>SOX</b>: SOX addresses financial reporting and corporate accountability, not privacy rights.</span><span class='qd'><b>GLBA</b>: GLBA covers U.S. financial-institution customer data, not EU data-subject rights.</span>"},{"id":"D6-014","domain":6,"obj":"6.3","diff":"medium","q":"An internal audit team compares the organization's current cloud control set against the CSA Cloud Controls Matrix to identify where controls are missing or immature. What is this activity called?","options":["Penetration test","Gap analysis","Chain-of-custody review","Data classification"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Gap analysis</strong> — measuring existing controls against a target framework to reveal deficiencies is a gap analysis.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Penetration test</b>: a pen test actively exploits weaknesses; it does not systematically map controls to a framework.</span><span class='qd'><b>Chain-of-custody review</b>: this concerns evidence handling in forensics, not control coverage.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data classification</b>: classification assigns sensitivity labels to data, not a control-coverage comparison.</span>"},{"id":"D6-015","domain":6,"obj":"6.2","diff":"easy","q":"Which standard specifically addresses the protection of Personally Identifiable Information (PII) in public cloud environments where the provider acts as a processor?","options":["ISO/IEC 27001","ISO/IEC 27050","ISO/IEC 27018","ISO/IEC 20000-1"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>ISO/IEC 27018</strong> — this code of practice extends privacy controls specifically for public-cloud providers acting as PII processors.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO/IEC 27001</b>: it defines the general ISMS requirements, not cloud-PII-specific processor controls.</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO/IEC 20000-1</b>: it addresses IT service management, not privacy.</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO/IEC 27050</b>: it addresses electronic discovery, not PII protection in public clouds.</span>"},{"id":"D6-016","domain":6,"obj":"6.2","diff":"hard","q":"A cloud customer is the data controller and its provider is the processor. A breach occurs at the provider affecting personal data. Under most modern breach-notification regimes, who is ultimately accountable for notifying the supervisory authority and affected individuals?","options":["The provider alone, because the breach occurred on its systems","The cloud broker","No one, if the data was encrypted at rest","The controller, though the processor must promptly inform the controller"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The controller, though the processor must promptly inform the controller</strong> — accountability for notification rests with the controller, while the processor is obligated to notify the controller without undue delay so it can act.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The provider alone, because the breach occurred on its systems</b>: the processor's location of the breach does not transfer notification accountability away from the controller.</span><span class='qd'><b>The cloud broker</b>: a broker intermediates services and is not the accountable party for controller notification duties.</span><span class='qd'><b>No one, if the data was encrypted at rest</b>: encryption may reduce obligations in some regimes but does not universally eliminate the duty to assess and notify.</span>"},{"id":"D6-017","domain":6,"obj":"6.3","diff":"medium","q":"A customer worries that if its SaaS vendor goes bankrupt, it will lose access to critical application source code needed to maintain the service. Which contractual mechanism BEST addresses this concern?","options":["Source-code escrow","Cyber-insurance","Service credits","Right-to-audit"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Source-code escrow</strong> — a neutral third party holds the source code and releases it under defined conditions such as vendor insolvency, protecting the customer's continuity.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Cyber-insurance</b>: insurance covers financial loss from incidents, not access to source code on vendor failure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Right-to-audit</b>: audit rights let you inspect controls, not obtain code if the vendor collapses.</span><span class='qd'><b>Service credits</b>: credits compensate for missed SLAs but do not deliver source code.</span>"},{"id":"D6-018","domain":6,"obj":"6.1","diff":"easy","q":"A legal team issues a directive that specific cloud data relevant to anticipated litigation must not be altered or deleted, overriding normal retention schedules. What is this directive called?","options":["Data classification","Legal hold","Tokenization","Right to be forgotten"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Legal hold</strong> — a legal hold (litigation hold) suspends routine deletion so potentially relevant evidence is preserved.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Data classification</b>: classification labels sensitivity; it does not freeze deletion for litigation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Tokenization</b>: tokenization substitutes sensitive values, unrelated to preservation duties.</span><span class='qd'><b>Right to be forgotten</b>: this is a data-subject right to erasure, essentially the opposite of a hold.</span>"},{"id":"D6-019","domain":6,"obj":"6.3","diff":"hard","q":"A cloud provider's SOC 2 report includes a scope statement limiting the examination to a single region and a subset of services. A customer using a different region relies on the report as full assurance. What is the primary problem?","options":["The report is a Type I and cannot be trusted","SOC 2 cannot address availability","The audit scope restriction means the customer's region may be unassessed","The report must be a SOC 1 for cloud services"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The audit scope restriction means the customer's region may be unassessed</strong> — scope statements bound what was examined; relying on a report whose scope excludes your region gives false assurance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The report is a Type I and cannot be trusted</b>: the flaw is scope coverage, not the Type; a Type II can still have a limited scope.</span><span class='qd'><b>SOC 2 cannot address availability</b>: availability is one of the Trust Services Criteria SOC 2 can cover.</span><span class='qd'><b>The report must be a SOC 1 for cloud services</b>: SOC 1 targets financial-reporting controls and is not the right report for cloud security assurance.</span>"},{"id":"D6-020","domain":6,"obj":"6.2","diff":"medium","q":"A privacy officer distinguishes between data the organization must protect because of a signed customer agreement versus data protected because a statute mandates it. The customer-agreement category is BEST described as which type of private data?","options":["Regulated private data","Public data","Anonymized data","Contractual private data"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Contractual private data</strong> — protection obligations arising from agreements (such as an SLA or DPA) rather than statute define contractual private data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Regulated private data</b>: regulated data is protected because law requires it, not because of a contract.</span><span class='qd'><b>Public data</b>: public data carries no confidentiality obligation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Anonymized data</b>: anonymized data has had identifiers removed and generally falls outside private-data obligations.</span>"},{"id":"D6-021","domain":6,"obj":"6.3","diff":"medium","q":"An enterprise risk manager evaluating a cloud provider requests evidence of the provider's own risk-management program, control maturity, and third-party attestations. This activity is BEST described as assessing the provider's what?","options":["Risk management program","Right-to-audit clause","SLA credits","Data classification scheme"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Risk management program</strong> — evaluating a provider's governance, control maturity, and attestations is an assessment of its risk-management program, a core cloud ERM activity.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Right-to-audit clause</b>: that is a single contract term, not the program-level evaluation described.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data classification scheme</b>: classification concerns labeling data sensitivity, not evaluating the provider's risk posture.</span><span class='qd'><b>SLA credits</b>: credits are a remedy mechanism, not an evaluation of a risk program.</span>"},{"id":"D6-022","domain":6,"obj":"6.3","diff":"easy","q":"Two organizations sign a high-level agreement establishing the overall terms, responsibilities, and legal framework governing all future work between them, under which individual statements of work will be issued. What is this document?","options":["Service Level Agreement (SLA)","Master Services Agreement (MSA)","Non-Disclosure Agreement (NDA)","Statement of Work (SOW)"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Master Services Agreement (MSA)</strong> — the MSA sets the governing terms under which subsequent SOWs define specific deliverables.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Service Level Agreement (SLA)</b>: an SLA specifies measurable service targets, not the overarching legal framework.</span><span class='qd'><b>Statement of Work (SOW)</b>: an SOW details a specific engagement's scope and is issued under an MSA.</span><span class='qd'><b>Non-Disclosure Agreement (NDA)</b>: an NDA governs confidentiality only, not the full relationship.</span>"},{"id":"D6-023","domain":6,"obj":"6.3","diff":"medium","q":"An organization must comply with the standard mandating protection of cardholder data for any system that stores, processes, or transmits payment card information. Which compliance regime applies?","options":["HITECH","NERC CIP","PCI DSS","SOX"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>PCI DSS</strong> — the Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard governs the handling of cardholder data across storage, processing, and transmission.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>HITECH</b>: HITECH strengthens HIPAA health-data provisions, not payment cards.</span><span class='qd'><b>NERC CIP</b>: NERC CIP protects critical electric-infrastructure assets, not cardholder data.</span><span class='qd'><b>SOX</b>: SOX addresses financial-reporting integrity, not payment-card security.</span>"},{"id":"D6-024","domain":6,"obj":"6.3","diff":"hard","q":"A board asks the CISO to express aggregate cloud risk in a way that supports comparison across business units and tracking over time. Which deliverable BEST satisfies this?","options":["A single penetration-test report","The provider's SOC 3","The data retention policy","A set of standardized risk metrics"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>A set of standardized risk metrics</strong> — consistent, quantifiable risk metrics enable comparison across units and trend tracking over time.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A single penetration-test report</b>: a point-in-time pen test does not provide comparable, ongoing aggregate metrics.</span><span class='qd'><b>The provider's SOC 3</b>: a SOC 3 is a provider assurance summary, not the organization's cross-unit risk view.</span><span class='qd'><b>The data retention policy</b>: retention rules govern data lifecycle, not aggregate risk measurement.</span>"},{"id":"D6-025","domain":6,"obj":"6.1","diff":"medium","q":"CSA guidance notes that in cloud environments, the data an organization must produce during eDiscovery may be commingled with other tenants' data on shared infrastructure. What is the PRIMARY concern this raises?","options":["Ensuring only the organization's own responsive data is collected without exposing other tenants","Achieving a higher SLA uptime","Reducing storage cost","Improving network latency"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Ensuring only the organization's own responsive data is collected without exposing other tenants</strong> — multi-tenant commingling makes precise, isolated collection of just the relevant data a core eDiscovery challenge.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Achieving a higher SLA uptime</b>: availability targets are unrelated to isolating responsive discovery data.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reducing storage cost</b>: cost efficiency is not the legal concern in commingled eDiscovery.</span><span class='qd'><b>Improving network latency</b>: latency is a performance metric, not an eDiscovery isolation concern.</span>"},{"id":"D6-026","domain":6,"obj":"6.2","diff":"hard","q":"A U.S. company transfers EU personal data to its U.S. cloud region. To do so lawfully under GDPR in the absence of an adequacy decision, which mechanism is commonly used?","options":["A SOC 2 Type II report","Standard Contractual Clauses (SCCs)","A force majeure clause","A legal hold"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Standard Contractual Clauses (SCCs)</strong> — SCCs are an approved transfer mechanism providing appropriate safeguards for cross-border transfers where no adequacy decision exists.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A SOC 2 Type II report</b>: SOC 2 is a control-assurance report, not a lawful transfer mechanism.</span><span class='qd'><b>A legal hold</b>: a legal hold preserves data for litigation and does not authorize transfers.</span><span class='qd'><b>A force majeure clause</b>: force majeure excuses performance during emergencies, unrelated to data-transfer legality.</span>"},{"id":"D6-027","domain":6,"obj":"6.3","diff":"medium","q":"An organization's audit committee wants an examination performed by a party with no operational stake in the systems, to satisfy regulators and customers who require impartial assurance. Which type of audit is required?","options":["Internal audit","Self-assessment","External (independent third-party) audit","Peer review"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>External (independent third-party) audit</strong> — regulators and customers requiring impartial assurance typically demand an independent external auditor with no operational stake.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Internal audit</b>: internal auditors, while valuable, lack the independence external stakeholders often require.</span><span class='qd'><b>Self-assessment</b>: a self-assessment is performed by the organization itself and carries the least independence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Peer review</b>: a peer review among colleagues does not provide independent third-party assurance.</span>"},{"id":"D6-028","domain":6,"obj":"6.3","diff":"medium","q":"A finance-sector organization must comply with a U.S. law requiring executives to attest to the accuracy of financial reports and mandating internal controls over financial reporting, which extends to cloud systems handling that data. Which law is this?","options":["GDPR","CCPA","HIPAA","SOX (Sarbanes-Oxley)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>SOX (Sarbanes-Oxley)</strong> — SOX requires executive attestation and internal controls over financial reporting, which reach any cloud systems processing financial data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>GDPR</b>: GDPR governs personal-data protection, not financial-reporting attestation.</span><span class='qd'><b>HIPAA</b>: HIPAA covers health information, not financial reporting controls.</span><span class='qd'><b>CCPA</b>: the CCPA is a consumer-privacy law, not a financial-reporting statute.</span>"},{"id":"D6-029","domain":6,"obj":"6.3","diff":"hard","q":"A customer is negotiating a cloud contract and wants to reduce the chance that migrating away later will be prohibitively difficult or expensive. Which pair of concerns is MOST directly relevant to address in the contract?","options":["Vendor lock-in and data portability/reversibility","Force majeure and NDAs","SLA credits and cyber-insurance","Chain of custody and non-repudiation"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Vendor lock-in and data portability/reversibility</strong> — addressing lock-in and ensuring portability/reversibility terms directly reduce the cost and difficulty of exiting a provider.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Force majeure and NDAs</b>: these govern emergencies and confidentiality, not exit portability.</span><span class='qd'><b>SLA credits and cyber-insurance</b>: these address service failures and financial loss, not migration difficulty.</span><span class='qd'><b>Chain of custody and non-repudiation</b>: these are forensic/evidence concepts, unrelated to provider exit.</span>"},{"id":"D6-030","domain":6,"obj":"6.1","diff":"medium","q":"In a cloud forensic investigation, an analyst must ensure that a captured disk image has not been altered since acquisition, so it will be admissible. Which technique BEST provides this assurance?","options":["Compressing the image","Generating and verifying a cryptographic hash of the image","Encrypting the network link","Applying data masking"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Generating and verifying a cryptographic hash of the image</strong> — a hash taken at acquisition and re-verified proves the evidence is unaltered, supporting integrity and admissibility.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Compressing the image</b>: compression reduces size but does not prove integrity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Encrypting the network link</b>: link encryption protects data in transit, not the stored image's integrity over time.</span><span class='qd'><b>Applying data masking</b>: masking alters data values, which would actually undermine evidentiary integrity.</span>"},{"id":"D6-031","domain":6,"obj":"6.3","diff":"easy","q":"Which SOC report focuses specifically on a service organization's controls that are relevant to its customers' internal control over financial reporting?","options":["SOC 2","SOC 3","SOC 1","SOC for Cybersecurity"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>SOC 1</strong> — SOC 1 addresses controls at a service organization that affect user entities' internal control over financial reporting.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>SOC 2</b>: SOC 2 reports on Trust Services Criteria such as security and availability, not financial reporting.</span><span class='qd'><b>SOC 3</b>: SOC 3 is a public summary of SOC 2 subject matter, not financial-reporting controls.</span><span class='qd'><b>SOC for Cybersecurity</b>: this addresses an entity-wide cybersecurity risk program, not financial-reporting controls.</span>"},{"id":"D6-032","domain":6,"obj":"6.2","diff":"medium","q":"A cloud governance lead differentiates between the party legally accountable for personal data and the party that merely stores and safeguards it operationally on the accountable party's behalf. The operational safekeeping party is BEST described as the:","options":["Data controller","Regulator","Data subject","Data custodian"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Data custodian</strong> — the custodian handles operational storage and safeguarding of data on behalf of the accountable owner/controller.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Data controller</b>: the controller determines purpose and is accountable, not merely a safekeeper.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data subject</b>: the data subject is the individual described by the data, not a safekeeping party.</span><span class='qd'><b>Regulator</b>: a regulator oversees compliance and does not store the organization's data.</span>"},{"id":"D6-033","domain":6,"obj":"6.2","diff":"hard","q":"A privacy team must select a comprehensive set of generally accepted privacy principles to structure its cloud privacy program, covering management, notice, choice, collection, use, and disclosure. Which framework is designed for exactly this?","options":["GAPP (Generally Accepted Privacy Principles)","PCI DSS","ISO/IEC 27001","NIST SP 800-145"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>GAPP (Generally Accepted Privacy Principles)</strong> — GAPP organizes privacy management into principles such as notice, choice, collection, use, retention, and disclosure, structuring a privacy program.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO/IEC 27001</b>: it defines an ISMS broadly, not a dedicated set of privacy principles.</span><span class='qd'><b>PCI DSS</b>: PCI DSS is narrowly focused on cardholder-data security, not comprehensive privacy principles.</span><span class='qd'><b>NIST SP 800-145</b>: SP 800-145 defines cloud computing terms, not privacy principles.</span>"},{"id":"D6-034","domain":6,"obj":"6.3","diff":"medium","q":"An organization concludes that the risk of hosting a highly sensitive legacy application in a public cloud outweighs the benefits, so it decides not to migrate that application at all. Which risk treatment has it chosen?","options":["Risk acceptance","Risk avoidance","Risk transfer","Risk mitigation"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Risk avoidance</strong> — declining to undertake the activity that creates the risk (the migration) is risk avoidance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk acceptance</b>: acceptance would mean proceeding and tolerating the risk, not declining the activity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk transfer</b>: transfer shifts consequences to a third party, such as insurance, not avoiding the activity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk mitigation</b>: mitigation reduces risk while still proceeding, whereas here the activity is abandoned.</span>"},{"id":"D6-035","domain":6,"obj":"6.3","diff":"hard","q":"A CCSP is advising on assurance challenges unique to virtualized, multi-tenant cloud infrastructure during an audit. Which factor MOST complicates the auditor's ability to inspect underlying controls directly?","options":["The customer has full physical access to hosts","Cloud eliminates the need for audits","The abstraction and shared nature of infrastructure limits direct visibility into provider controls","Virtualization guarantees isolation, removing all audit concern"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The abstraction and shared nature of infrastructure limits direct visibility into provider controls</strong> — in multi-tenant clouds the auditor cannot directly inspect the shared hardware and hypervisor layers, so assurance relies on the provider's attestations.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The customer has full physical access to hosts</b>: customers generally do not have physical access in public cloud, which is precisely the difficulty.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cloud eliminates the need for audits</b>: cloud increases, not removes, the need for assurance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Virtualization guarantees isolation, removing all audit concern</b>: isolation is a control that itself must be audited and can fail.</span>"},{"id":"D6-036","domain":6,"obj":"6.3","diff":"medium","q":"A customer wants its cloud contract to define measurable service targets, with remedies if the provider falls short, so performance can be objectively enforced. Which contract element provides this?","options":["Statement of Work","Escrow agreement","Non-Disclosure Agreement","Service Level Agreement (SLA)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Service Level Agreement (SLA)</strong> — the SLA specifies measurable targets (e.g., uptime, response time) and the remedies, such as service credits, when they are missed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Statement of Work</b>: an SOW scopes deliverables and tasks, not ongoing measurable service levels and remedies.</span><span class='qd'><b>Non-Disclosure Agreement</b>: an NDA governs confidentiality, not performance metrics.</span><span class='qd'><b>Escrow agreement</b>: escrow protects assets on vendor failure, not day-to-day service targets.</span>"},{"id":"D6-037","domain":6,"obj":"6.1","diff":"medium","q":"A CCSP is asked which framework provides voluntary guidance and controls tailored specifically for cloud security assurance and provider evaluation, widely used for the CAIQ questionnaire. Which is it?","options":["CSA Cloud Controls Matrix (CCM)","PCI DSS","ISO 9001","COBIT"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>CSA Cloud Controls Matrix (CCM)</strong> — the CSA CCM is a cloud-specific control framework, and its companion CAIQ questionnaire is used to evaluate providers.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>PCI DSS</b>: PCI DSS is a payment-card security standard, not a general cloud control matrix.</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO 9001</b>: ISO 9001 concerns quality management, not cloud security controls.</span><span class='qd'><b>COBIT</b>: COBIT is an IT governance framework, not a cloud-specific control matrix with the CAIQ.</span>"},{"id":"D6-038","domain":6,"obj":"6.2","diff":"medium","q":"A jurisdiction requires that personal data about its citizens be stored and processed only within the country's borders. When choosing cloud regions, which requirement must the organization satisfy?","options":["Right-to-audit","Data residency / localization","Non-repudiation","Service credits"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Data residency / localization</strong> — laws mandating in-country storage and processing impose data-residency (localization) requirements on region selection.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Right-to-audit</b>: audit rights concern inspecting controls, not where data physically resides.</span><span class='qd'><b>Non-repudiation</b>: non-repudiation ensures actions cannot be denied, unrelated to storage location.</span><span class='qd'><b>Service credits</b>: credits remedy SLA breaches, not localization mandates.</span>"},{"id":"D6-039","domain":6,"obj":"6.3","diff":"easy","q":"After applying all feasible controls to a cloud risk, some risk still remains. The organization documents it and, with management sign-off, chooses to live with it. What is the remaining risk called, and what treatment was chosen?","options":["Inherent risk; avoidance","Total risk; transfer","Residual risk; acceptance","Zero risk; mitigation"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Residual risk; acceptance</strong> — the risk left after controls are applied is residual risk, and formally choosing to live with it is risk acceptance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Inherent risk; avoidance</b>: inherent risk is the risk before controls, and avoidance means not doing the activity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Total risk; transfer</b>: total risk is the full exposure before treatment, and transfer shifts it to a third party.</span><span class='qd'><b>Zero risk; mitigation</b>: risk is never truly zero, and mitigation reduces rather than eliminates it.</span>"},{"id":"D6-040","domain":6,"obj":"6.3","diff":"hard","q":"An electric utility moving grid-management systems to the cloud must comply with mandatory reliability standards protecting bulk electric-system cyber assets. Which specialized compliance regime applies?","options":["HITECH","GLBA","FERPA","NERC CIP"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>NERC CIP</strong> — the North American Electric Reliability Corporation Critical Infrastructure Protection standards govern security of bulk electric-system cyber assets.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>HITECH</b>: HITECH concerns electronic health records, not the power grid.</span><span class='qd'><b>GLBA</b>: GLBA governs financial-institution customer data, not electric reliability.</span><span class='qd'><b>FERPA</b>: FERPA protects student education records, unrelated to critical grid infrastructure.</span>"},{"id":"D6-041","domain":6,"obj":"6.1","diff":"medium","q":"A CCSP must advise on the correct order of eDiscovery activities per the reference model when responding to litigation involving cloud data. Which activity comes FIRST?","options":["Identification of potentially relevant data","Production","Review","Presentation"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Identification of potentially relevant data</strong> — the eDiscovery reference model begins with identifying potentially relevant ESI before it can be preserved, collected, and produced.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Production</b>: production is a late-stage step, delivering data to the requesting party.</span><span class='qd'><b>Review</b>: review of collected data occurs after identification, preservation, and collection.</span><span class='qd'><b>Presentation</b>: presentation is the final stage, displaying evidence, not the first.</span>"},{"id":"D6-042","domain":6,"obj":"6.3","diff":"medium","q":"A procurement team must evaluate whether a prospective cloud provider is financially stable enough to remain in business for the life of a multi-year contract. Which vendor-management concern is this?","options":["Non-repudiation","Vendor viability","Right-to-audit","Data classification"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Vendor viability</strong> — assessing a provider's financial stability and likelihood of remaining operational is a vendor-viability evaluation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Right-to-audit</b>: this is a contractual inspection right, not a viability assessment.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data classification</b>: classification labels data sensitivity, not provider solvency.</span><span class='qd'><b>Non-repudiation</b>: non-repudiation is a security property of transactions, unrelated to vendor stability.</span>"},{"id":"D6-043","domain":6,"obj":"6.2","diff":"medium","q":"A regulator requires that whenever a breach of personal data meets a defined threshold, the organization must inform authorities and affected individuals within a set timeframe. This obligation is an example of regulatory:","options":["Escrow","Risk avoidance","Transparency (breach notification)","Tokenization"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Transparency (breach notification)</strong> — mandatory breach notification within set timeframes is a form of regulatory transparency obligating disclosure to authorities and individuals.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk avoidance</b>: avoidance is a treatment decision, not a disclosure obligation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Escrow</b>: escrow safeguards assets against vendor failure, unrelated to breach disclosure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Tokenization</b>: tokenization is a data-protection technique, not a notification duty.</span>"},{"id":"D6-044","domain":6,"obj":"6.3","diff":"medium","q":"A cloud audit program distinguishes among policy levels. Which policy type sets the highest-level, enterprise-wide direction and management intent that lower-level policies must support?","options":["Functional policy","Cloud-specific policy","System configuration standard","Organizational (corporate) policy"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Organizational (corporate) policy</strong> — organizational policy expresses top-level management intent and enterprise-wide direction that functional and cloud-specific policies must align to.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Functional policy</b>: functional policies address specific areas (e.g., access control) beneath the organizational level.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cloud-specific policy</b>: cloud policies apply the organizational direction to cloud contexts, not the highest level.</span><span class='qd'><b>System configuration standard</b>: a configuration standard is an implementation detail, far below the policy apex.</span>"},{"id":"D6-045","domain":6,"obj":"6.2","diff":"hard","q":"A global service operates in several countries with differing privacy laws. Legal wants a defensible way to determine which country's law governs a given user's data. Which factor is MOST central to resolving these jurisdictional differences?","options":["Where the data subject resides and where processing occurs, per each applicable law's scope","The physical location of the provider's headquarters only","The color of the data classification label","The provider's SOC 3 report"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Where the data subject resides and where processing occurs, per each applicable law's scope</strong> — jurisdiction commonly turns on the data subject's location and the place of processing, as each statute defines its own territorial reach.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The physical location of the provider's headquarters only</b>: HQ location alone does not determine applicability; laws like GDPR reach based on subjects and activities.</span><span class='qd'><b>The color of the data classification label</b>: labeling schemes do not decide legal jurisdiction.</span><span class='qd'><b>The provider's SOC 3 report</b>: a SOC 3 is an assurance summary, not a determinant of governing law.</span>"},{"id":"D6-046","domain":6,"obj":"6.3","diff":"hard","q":"A CCSP reviews a cloud outsourcing arrangement and wants to apply the standard that specifically addresses information security in supplier and supply-chain relationships. Which standard is it?","options":["ISO/IEC 27017","ISO/IEC 27036","ISO/IEC 27018","ISO/IEC 27701"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>ISO/IEC 27036</strong> — this standard addresses information security for supplier relationships and supply-chain management, directly applicable to cloud outsourcing.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO/IEC 27017</b>: it provides cloud security controls generally, not supplier-relationship-specific guidance.</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO/IEC 27018</b>: it addresses PII protection in public clouds, not supply-chain security.</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO/IEC 27701</b>: it extends the ISMS for privacy management, not supplier relationships specifically.</span>"},{"id":"D6-047","domain":6,"obj":"6.3","diff":"medium","q":"During a cloud risk assessment, the team evaluates the broader context, including threat landscape, regulatory pressures, and business objectives, before deciding on treatments. This step is BEST described as:","options":["Data masking","Chain-of-custody verification","Risk environment assessment","Penetration testing"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Risk environment assessment</strong> — evaluating the surrounding threat, regulatory, and business context to frame risk decisions is a risk environment assessment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Chain-of-custody verification</b>: this concerns evidence handling in forensics, not risk context.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data masking</b>: masking obscures data values, unrelated to assessing the risk environment.</span><span class='qd'><b>Penetration testing</b>: a pen test finds technical weaknesses, not the broad regulatory/business context.</span>"},{"id":"D6-048","domain":6,"obj":"6.1","diff":"easy","q":"A cloud investigation must ensure that log entries can be reliably attributed to a specific user and that the user cannot later deny performing the action. Which property supports admissibility here?","options":["Elasticity","Multi-tenancy","Reversibility","Non-repudiation"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Non-repudiation</strong> — non-repudiation binds actions to actors so a party cannot credibly deny having performed them, supporting evidentiary reliability.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Elasticity</b>: elasticity is a scaling characteristic of cloud, not an evidentiary property.</span><span class='qd'><b>Multi-tenancy</b>: multi-tenancy describes shared infrastructure, unrelated to attribution of actions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reversibility</b>: reversibility concerns the ability to exit a provider, not evidence attribution.</span>"},{"id":"D6-049","domain":6,"obj":"6.3","diff":"hard","q":"An organization's audit plan for its cloud environment must account for the fact that its data and workloads are spread across many locations and providers. What is the PRIMARY impact of this distributed IT model on the audit?","options":["It complicates defining scope and gathering evidence across dispersed, provider-controlled environments","It eliminates the need for scope statements","It guarantees continuous real-time assurance","It removes reliance on provider attestations"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>It complicates defining scope and gathering evidence across dispersed, provider-controlled environments</strong> — distributed, multi-provider IT makes it harder to bound the audit scope and collect consistent evidence you do not directly control.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It eliminates the need for scope statements</b>: distribution makes scope statements more important, not unnecessary.</span><span class='qd'><b>It guarantees continuous real-time assurance</b>: distribution does not automatically provide continuous assurance.</span><span class='qd'><b>It removes reliance on provider attestations</b>: reliance on provider attestations typically increases when you cannot inspect directly.</span>"},{"id":"D6-050","domain":6,"obj":"6.3","diff":"medium","q":"A cloud contract nears its end and the customer wants assurance that, upon termination, its data will be returned in a usable format and securely deleted from the provider. Which contract provisions MOST directly address this?","options":["SLA uptime and service credits","Termination and data-portability/deletion clauses","Force majeure and NDA clauses","Right-to-audit and escrow only"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Termination and data-portability/deletion clauses</strong> — clear termination terms combined with data-return (portability) and secure-deletion clauses ensure the customer recovers usable data and confirms provider deletion at exit.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Force majeure and NDA clauses</b>: these govern emergencies and confidentiality, not end-of-contract data return and deletion.</span><span class='qd'><b>SLA uptime and service credits</b>: these address in-service performance, not exit data handling.</span><span class='qd'><b>Right-to-audit and escrow only</b>: while useful, alone they do not guarantee data return in a usable format and secure deletion at termination.</span>"},{"id":"D6-051","domain":6,"obj":"6.4","diff":"easy","q":"An organization decides to purchase cyber-insurance to offset the financial impact of a potential cloud data breach it cannot fully prevent. Which risk treatment does this represent?","options":["Risk avoidance","Risk acceptance","Risk transfer","Risk mitigation"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Risk transfer</strong> — shifting the financial consequences of a risk to a third party (here, an insurer) while the underlying risk still exists is the textbook definition of transference.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk avoidance</b>: avoidance means ceasing the activity that creates the risk entirely, not buying a policy to cover its cost.</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk acceptance</b>: acceptance means the organization retains the risk and absorbs any loss itself, which is the opposite of buying insurance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk mitigation</b>: mitigation reduces likelihood or impact through controls; a policy does not lower the probability of the breach occurring.</span>"},{"id":"D6-052","domain":6,"obj":"6.4","diff":"easy","q":"In a cloud arrangement, an organization determines the purposes and means of processing personal data and dictates how the CSP may handle it. Under privacy law terminology, what is this organization?","options":["Data processor","Data custodian","Data subject","Data controller"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Data controller</strong> — the party that decides the purposes and means of processing personal data is the controller and bears primary accountability for lawful handling.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Data processor</b>: the processor acts on the controller's instructions; that role fits the CSP, not the organization directing the processing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data custodian</b>: custodian is an operational data-management role, not the legally accountable party defining processing purposes.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data subject</b>: the data subject is the individual the personal data is about, not the organization processing it.</span>"},{"id":"D6-053","domain":6,"obj":"6.5","diff":"easy","q":"A company is negotiating a cloud contract and wants a documented commitment on uptime, response times, and remedies if targets are missed. Which contract artifact captures these measurable service commitments?","options":["Service Level Agreement (SLA)","Master Services Agreement (MSA)","Statement of Work (SOW)","Non-Disclosure Agreement (NDA)"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Service Level Agreement (SLA)</strong> — the SLA defines measurable service targets (uptime, response time) and the credits or remedies owed when they are not met.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Master Services Agreement (MSA)</b>: the MSA sets overarching legal terms of the relationship but does not itself specify the performance metrics.</span><span class='qd'><b>Statement of Work (SOW)</b>: the SOW describes specific deliverables and tasks for an engagement, not ongoing service-level remedies.</span><span class='qd'><b>Non-Disclosure Agreement (NDA)</b>: an NDA governs confidentiality of shared information, unrelated to uptime commitments.</span>"},{"id":"D6-054","domain":6,"obj":"6.5","diff":"medium","q":"A financial firm worries that if its niche SaaS vendor goes bankrupt, it will lose access to the source code needed to keep a critical application running. Which contractual mechanism best addresses this concern?","options":["Right-to-audit clause","Software escrow arrangement","Cyber-insurance rider","Data portability clause"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Software escrow arrangement</strong> — placing source code (and build instructions) with a neutral third party that releases it on defined triggers such as vendor insolvency directly protects continuity if the vendor fails.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Right-to-audit clause</b>: audit rights let you inspect controls but do nothing to preserve code access after a bankruptcy.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cyber-insurance rider</b>: insurance may reimburse losses but will not deliver the source code needed to run the application.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data portability clause</b>: portability covers moving your data out, not obtaining the vendor's proprietary source code.</span>"},{"id":"D6-055","domain":6,"obj":"6.4","diff":"medium","q":"A regional privacy regulation requires that affected individuals be informed within 72 hours of a confirmed personal-data breach. Which enterprise risk consideration does this obligation most directly reflect?","options":["Risk appetite alignment","Vendor lock-in avoidance","Regulatory transparency and breach notification","Quantitative risk scoring"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Regulatory transparency and breach notification</strong> — mandatory timely disclosure of breaches to individuals and regulators is a transparency obligation that enterprise risk programs must plan for.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk appetite alignment</b>: appetite concerns how much risk the organization will accept, not statutory disclosure timelines.</span><span class='qd'><b>Vendor lock-in avoidance</b>: lock-in is a portability/procurement concern, unrelated to breach reporting duties.</span><span class='qd'><b>Quantitative risk scoring</b>: scoring is an analysis technique, not a legal disclosure requirement.</span>"},{"id":"D6-056","domain":6,"obj":"6.5","diff":"medium","q":"An enterprise is finalizing a cloud contract and wants the ability to independently verify the provider's security controls during the relationship. Which clause should it insist on?","options":["Limitation-of-liability clause","Force majeure clause","Indemnification clause","Right-to-audit clause"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Right-to-audit clause</strong> — this clause grants the customer (or its agents) the contractual ability to examine the provider's controls, which is essential when direct assurance is needed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Limitation-of-liability clause</b>: this caps the provider's financial exposure and gives no inspection rights.</span><span class='qd'><b>Force majeure clause</b>: force majeure excuses performance during extraordinary events, unrelated to auditing controls.</span><span class='qd'><b>Indemnification clause</b>: indemnification allocates who pays for third-party claims, not verification of controls.</span>"},{"id":"D6-057","domain":6,"obj":"6.4","diff":"medium","q":"During a cloud risk assessment, a security architect must evaluate whether the CSP's own risk management program is mature and trustworthy. Which artifact provides the most credible independent evidence of the provider's control environment?","options":["An independent SOC 2 Type II report","The provider's marketing security whitepaper","The provider's public status page","The signed MSA between the parties"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>An independent SOC 2 Type II report</strong> — a third-party attestation over a period of time gives independent, tested evidence of the provider's control operating effectiveness, ideal for assessing its risk program.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The provider's marketing security whitepaper</b>: self-authored marketing lacks independence and testing.</span><span class='qd'><b>The provider's public status page</b>: a status page shows uptime events, not control maturity.</span><span class='qd'><b>The signed MSA between the parties</b>: the MSA sets legal terms but is not evidence that controls actually operate effectively.</span>"},{"id":"D6-058","domain":6,"obj":"6.5","diff":"medium","q":"A company relies on a single SaaS provider that uses proprietary data formats and APIs, making migration to any competitor extremely costly. Which vendor-management risk is most clearly present?","options":["Vendor viability risk","Vendor lock-in","Right-to-audit denial","Fourth-party risk"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Vendor lock-in</strong> — proprietary formats and APIs that make switching prohibitively expensive are the defining characteristic of lock-in risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Vendor viability risk</b>: viability concerns whether the vendor will survive financially, which is not what proprietary formats describe.</span><span class='qd'><b>Right-to-audit denial</b>: that concerns inability to inspect controls, not portability of data.</span><span class='qd'><b>Fourth-party risk</b>: fourth-party risk involves the vendor's own subcontractors, not format portability.</span>"},{"id":"D6-059","domain":6,"obj":"6.5","diff":"hard","q":"A cloud customer discovers that its SaaS vendor silently subcontracts data storage to a downstream provider the customer never assessed. Which supply-chain risk concept and governing standard are most relevant here?","options":["First-party risk; ISO/IEC 27001","Residual risk; ISO/IEC 31000","Fourth-party risk; ISO/IEC 27036","Inherent risk; ISO/IEC 27017"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Fourth-party risk; ISO/IEC 27036</strong> — risk introduced by a vendor's own subcontractors is fourth-party risk, and ISO/IEC 27036 provides guidance for information security in supplier relationships.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>First-party risk; ISO/IEC 27001</b>: first-party is the organization's own risk, and 27001 is an ISMS requirements standard, not supplier-relationship guidance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Residual risk; ISO/IEC 31000</b>: residual risk is what remains after controls; 31000 is general risk-management principles, not supply-chain focused.</span><span class='qd'><b>Inherent risk; ISO/IEC 27017</b>: inherent risk is pre-control risk, and 27017 addresses cloud security controls, not subcontractor governance.</span>"},{"id":"D6-060","domain":6,"obj":"6.4","diff":"medium","q":"After applying encryption, access controls, and monitoring to a cloud data store, the CISO documents the small amount of risk that still remains. What is this remaining risk called?","options":["Inherent risk","Transferred risk","Systemic risk","Residual risk"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Residual risk</strong> — the risk that persists after controls have been applied is residual risk, which leadership must formally accept or treat further.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Inherent risk</b>: inherent risk is the level before any controls are applied, not what remains after.</span><span class='qd'><b>Transferred risk</b>: transferred risk has been shifted to a third party, which is not what applying internal controls does.</span><span class='qd'><b>Systemic risk</b>: systemic risk refers to broad, cascading risk across a whole system or market, not leftover risk after controls.</span>"},{"id":"D6-061","domain":6,"obj":"6.4","diff":"easy","q":"A company chooses not to launch a new cloud-hosted product line at all because the associated regulatory exposure is deemed unacceptable. Which risk treatment strategy is this?","options":["Risk avoidance","Risk mitigation","Risk acceptance","Risk sharing"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Risk avoidance</strong> — declining to undertake the activity entirely so the risk never materializes is avoidance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk mitigation</b>: mitigation would proceed with the product but add controls to reduce risk, not cancel it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk acceptance</b>: acceptance would proceed and absorb the risk, the opposite of not launching.</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk sharing</b>: sharing would distribute the risk with partners while still pursuing the activity.</span>"},{"id":"D6-062","domain":6,"obj":"6.5","diff":"hard","q":"A multinational is drafting a cloud contract and wants assurance that the provider will keep meeting agreed metrics and that disputes can be litigated in a defined venue. Which set of contract-management elements most directly serves these needs?","options":["Force majeure and indemnification clauses","Metrics reporting and litigation/jurisdiction clauses","NDA scope and IP ownership clauses","Data classification and labeling schema"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Metrics reporting and litigation/jurisdiction clauses</strong> — ongoing metric reporting proves the provider keeps meeting targets, and litigation/governing-law clauses fix the forum and law for disputes.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Force majeure and indemnification clauses</b>: these handle excused performance and third-party claims, not metric tracking or dispute venue.</span><span class='qd'><b>NDA scope and IP ownership clauses</b>: these address confidentiality and intellectual property, not service metrics or litigation forum.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data classification and labeling schema</b>: classification is a data-handling control, not a contract-management remedy.</span>"},{"id":"D6-063","domain":6,"obj":"6.4","diff":"medium","q":"A cloud governance committee wants a common structured approach to identify, assess, and treat risk consistently across all cloud initiatives. Which of the following best meets this need?","options":["A single provider's marketing framework","A one-time penetration test report","An adopted enterprise risk framework such as NIST RMF or ISO 31000","The provider's default IAM policy"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>An adopted enterprise risk framework such as NIST RMF or ISO 31000</strong> — a recognized risk framework gives a repeatable, structured process for identifying, assessing, and treating risk across initiatives.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A single provider's marketing framework</b>: vendor marketing lacks the neutrality and rigor of an established framework.</span><span class='qd'><b>A one-time penetration test report</b>: a point-in-time test finds vulnerabilities but is not a governance framework.</span><span class='qd'><b>The provider's default IAM policy</b>: IAM policy governs access, not enterprise-wide risk methodology.</span>"},{"id":"D6-064","domain":6,"obj":"6.4","diff":"easy","q":"An organization decides the likelihood and impact of a rare cloud risk are so low that it will take no additional action and simply absorb any loss. What is this decision?","options":["Risk avoidance","Risk transfer","Risk mitigation","Risk acceptance"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Risk acceptance</strong> — knowingly retaining a risk and absorbing any resulting loss without further treatment is acceptance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk avoidance</b>: avoidance stops the activity; here the organization proceeds unchanged.</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk transfer</b>: transfer shifts consequences to a third party such as an insurer, which is not happening.</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk mitigation</b>: mitigation adds controls to reduce the risk, but the decision here is to take no action.</span>"},{"id":"D6-065","domain":6,"obj":"6.5","diff":"medium","q":"An enterprise is assessing whether a boutique cloud analytics startup will survive long enough to be a dependable multi-year partner, reviewing its funding, revenue, and customer base. Which vendor-management concern is being evaluated?","options":["Vendor viability","Vendor lock-in","Right-to-audit scope","Data residency"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Vendor viability</strong> — assessing a vendor's financial health and likelihood of remaining in business is a viability assessment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Vendor lock-in</b>: lock-in concerns difficulty of switching, not whether the vendor will stay solvent.</span><span class='qd'><b>Right-to-audit scope</b>: that concerns inspection rights, not financial durability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data residency</b>: residency addresses where data is physically stored, unrelated to vendor solvency.</span>"},{"id":"D6-066","domain":6,"obj":"6.4","diff":"hard","q":"A U.S.-listed company migrates its financial reporting systems to a public cloud. Executives must certify the accuracy of financial statements and the effectiveness of related internal controls. Which regulatory driver most directly shapes the cloud control requirements here?","options":["GDPR","Sarbanes-Oxley (SOX)","PCI DSS","HIPAA"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Sarbanes-Oxley (SOX)</strong> — SOX requires executives of publicly traded U.S. companies to attest to financial-statement accuracy and internal control effectiveness, directly shaping controls over cloud-hosted financial systems.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>GDPR</b>: GDPR governs personal data of EU residents, not financial-reporting internal controls.</span><span class='qd'><b>PCI DSS</b>: PCI DSS protects cardholder data, not corporate financial statements.</span><span class='qd'><b>HIPAA</b>: HIPAA covers protected health information, irrelevant to financial reporting attestation.</span>"},{"id":"D6-067","domain":6,"obj":"6.5","diff":"medium","q":"A customer wants its cloud contract to allow a clean exit: return of all data in a usable format, deletion of residual copies, and reasonable transition assistance. Which clause should be prioritized?","options":["Indemnification clause","Force majeure clause","Termination and exit clause","Confidentiality clause"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Termination and exit clause</strong> — a well-drafted termination clause specifies data return in usable form, secure deletion of residual copies, and transition support, enabling a clean exit.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Indemnification clause</b>: indemnification allocates liability for third-party claims, not exit logistics.</span><span class='qd'><b>Force majeure clause</b>: force majeure excuses performance during extraordinary events, not orderly offboarding.</span><span class='qd'><b>Confidentiality clause</b>: confidentiality protects shared information but does not govern data return on exit.</span>"},{"id":"D6-068","domain":6,"obj":"6.4","diff":"medium","q":"A cloud program office wants to track whether its risk posture is improving over time using indicators like number of overdue high-risk findings and mean time to remediate. What are these indicators best described as?","options":["Control baselines","Audit scope statements","Data flow diagrams","Risk metrics"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Risk metrics</strong> — quantifiable indicators such as overdue findings and mean time to remediate are risk metrics used to monitor and communicate posture over time.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Control baselines</b>: baselines are minimum required control sets, not measures of posture trends.</span><span class='qd'><b>Audit scope statements</b>: scope statements define audit boundaries, not ongoing performance indicators.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data flow diagrams</b>: data flow diagrams map how data moves, not risk performance over time.</span>"},{"id":"D6-069","domain":6,"obj":"6.4","diff":"hard","q":"Two business units interpret a shared cloud risk differently: one calls it 'high' and treats it aggressively, the other calls it 'moderate' and defers action. The CISO wants to prevent this inconsistency going forward. Which governance improvement most directly addresses the root cause?","options":["Define an enterprise risk appetite and standardized risk-rating criteria","Buy more cyber-insurance","Switch to a different cloud provider","Increase penetration testing frequency"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Define an enterprise risk appetite and standardized risk-rating criteria</strong> — a common appetite statement and consistent scoring criteria ensure the same risk is rated and treated uniformly across business units.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Buy more cyber-insurance</b>: insurance transfers cost but does nothing to align inconsistent risk ratings.</span><span class='qd'><b>Switch to a different cloud provider</b>: changing providers does not fix an internal governance inconsistency.</span><span class='qd'><b>Increase penetration testing frequency</b>: more testing finds vulnerabilities but does not standardize how risk is rated.</span>"},{"id":"D6-070","domain":6,"obj":"6.5","diff":"medium","q":"A customer's SLA promises 99.9% monthly availability. During a month the provider delivers 99.2%. The customer wants a predefined consequence rather than having to sue. Which SLA element provides this?","options":["Indemnification","Service credits","Escrow release","Chain of custody"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Service credits</strong> — SLAs typically define service credits (billing reductions) as the predefined remedy when availability targets are missed, avoiding litigation for routine shortfalls.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Indemnification</b>: indemnification covers third-party claim liability, not SLA target misses.</span><span class='qd'><b>Escrow release</b>: escrow release delivers source code on vendor failure, unrelated to an availability shortfall.</span><span class='qd'><b>Chain of custody</b>: chain of custody is a forensic evidence concept, not an SLA remedy.</span>"},{"id":"D6-071","domain":6,"obj":"6.4","diff":"easy","q":"In cloud data-protection terminology, which party is responsible for handling personal data only according to the controller's documented instructions?","options":["Data subject","Data owner","Data processor","Regulator"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Data processor</strong> — the processor handles personal data strictly on the controller's documented instructions and does not determine the purposes of processing.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Data subject</b>: the data subject is the individual whom the data concerns, not a processing party.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data owner</b>: the data owner (often aligned with the controller) sets purposes and accountability, not merely follows instructions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Regulator</b>: the regulator enforces the law and does not process data on a controller's behalf.</span>"},{"id":"D6-072","domain":6,"obj":"6.5","diff":"hard","q":"A procurement team wants a hierarchy of documents where broad legal terms are set once and reused across many future projects, with each project's specifics attached separately. Which combination correctly reflects this structure?","options":["SOW as the umbrella, MSA per project","SLA as the umbrella, MSA per project","NDA as the umbrella, SOW per project","MSA as the umbrella, SOW per project"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>MSA as the umbrella, SOW per project</strong> — the Master Services Agreement establishes reusable legal terms once, while each Statement of Work attaches project-specific scope, deliverables, and timelines under it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>SOW as the umbrella, MSA per project</b>: this inverts the hierarchy; the SOW is the project-specific document, not the umbrella.</span><span class='qd'><b>SLA as the umbrella, MSA per project</b>: an SLA defines service metrics and is not the overarching legal agreement.</span><span class='qd'><b>NDA as the umbrella, SOW per project</b>: an NDA only covers confidentiality and cannot serve as the master legal framework.</span>"},{"id":"D6-073","domain":6,"obj":"6.4","diff":"medium","q":"A CCSP advisor is asked whether moving a workload to a public cloud eliminates the customer's accountability for protecting regulated data. What is the correct guidance?","options":["No; the customer remains accountable even though some responsibilities are shared","Yes; the provider becomes fully accountable once data is in their cloud","Only if a SOC 2 report exists","Only for IaaS, not SaaS"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>No; the customer remains accountable even though some responsibilities are shared</strong> — under shared responsibility, operational tasks may shift to the provider, but legal accountability for regulated data stays with the customer/controller.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Yes; the provider becomes fully accountable once data is in their cloud</b>: providers are typically processors and do not assume the controller's legal accountability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only if a SOC 2 report exists</b>: a SOC 2 report is assurance evidence, not a transfer of accountability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only for IaaS, not SaaS</b>: accountability for regulated data remains with the customer across all service models.</span>"},{"id":"D6-074","domain":6,"obj":"6.5","diff":"medium","q":"Before signing, an enterprise runs a structured evaluation of a prospective CSP covering its certifications, financial stability, security controls, and subprocessors. What is this activity called?","options":["Business impact analysis","Vendor risk assessment","Gap analysis","Data discovery"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Vendor risk assessment</strong> — evaluating a prospective vendor's certifications, financials, controls, and subprocessors before engagement is a vendor (third-party) risk assessment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Business impact analysis</b>: a BIA determines the impact of disruptions to your own processes, not a vendor's control posture.</span><span class='qd'><b>Gap analysis</b>: gap analysis compares current state to a target standard, not a holistic vendor evaluation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data discovery</b>: data discovery locates and classifies data, unrelated to evaluating a vendor.</span>"},{"id":"D6-075","domain":6,"obj":"6.4","diff":"hard","q":"A hospital using a cloud EHR splits duties so that the hospital defines lawful uses of patient records while the cloud vendor merely stores and processes them per contract. Mapping this to privacy roles, which pairing is correct?","options":["Hospital = processor; vendor = controller","Hospital = data subject; vendor = controller","Hospital = controller; vendor = processor","Hospital = custodian; vendor = data subject"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Hospital = controller; vendor = processor</strong> — the hospital determines the purposes and lawful uses (controller), and the vendor processes the data on the hospital's instructions (processor).<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Hospital = processor; vendor = controller</b>: this reverses the roles; the vendor does not set the purposes of processing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Hospital = data subject; vendor = controller</b>: the data subjects are the patients, not the hospital.</span><span class='qd'><b>Hospital = custodian; vendor = data subject</b>: neither label fits; the vendor is certainly not the data subject.</span>"},{"id":"D6-076","domain":6,"obj":"6.5","diff":"easy","q":"Which document most precisely defines the specific deliverables, milestones, and acceptance criteria for a single cloud migration project?","options":["Service Level Agreement (SLA)","Non-Disclosure Agreement (NDA)","Business Associate Agreement (BAA)","Statement of Work (SOW)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Statement of Work (SOW)</strong> — the SOW enumerates the specific deliverables, milestones, timelines, and acceptance criteria for a defined engagement.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Service Level Agreement (SLA)</b>: the SLA defines ongoing service performance metrics, not project deliverables.</span><span class='qd'><b>Non-Disclosure Agreement (NDA)</b>: the NDA governs confidentiality only.</span><span class='qd'><b>Business Associate Agreement (BAA)</b>: a BAA is a HIPAA-specific data-protection contract, not a project scope document.</span>"},{"id":"D6-077","domain":6,"obj":"6.4","diff":"medium","q":"A risk committee wants to convert identified cloud risks into dollar figures using estimates of asset value, exposure factor, and annual rate of occurrence. Which analysis approach are they using?","options":["Quantitative risk analysis","Qualitative risk analysis","Threat modeling","Root cause analysis"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Quantitative risk analysis</strong> — using values like asset value, exposure factor (SLE) and annual rate of occurrence to derive annualized loss expectancy is quantitative analysis.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Qualitative risk analysis</b>: qualitative analysis uses relative ratings (high/medium/low), not monetary calculations.</span><span class='qd'><b>Threat modeling</b>: threat modeling identifies and enumerates threats to a system, not loss expectancy figures.</span><span class='qd'><b>Root cause analysis</b>: root cause analysis investigates why an incident occurred, not risk valuation.</span>"},{"id":"D6-078","domain":6,"obj":"6.5","diff":"hard","q":"A customer negotiating with a large hyperscaler finds the provider will not accept a traditional customer-led on-site audit. Which alternative most reasonably satisfies the customer's assurance needs while respecting the provider's scale?","options":["Waive assurance entirely and trust the brand","Rely on the provider's independent third-party audit reports (e.g., SOC 2, ISO 27001)","Demand physical access to all data centers","Substitute a penetration test of the provider's corporate website"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Rely on the provider's independent third-party audit reports (e.g., SOC 2, ISO 27001)</strong> — hyperscalers commonly provide independent attestations in lieu of individual customer audits, giving credible assurance at scale.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Waive assurance entirely and trust the brand</b>: abandoning all assurance is not a defensible risk decision.</span><span class='qd'><b>Demand physical access to all data centers</b>: mass physical access is impractical and typically refused for security reasons.</span><span class='qd'><b>Substitute a penetration test of the provider's corporate website</b>: a website pentest reveals nothing about the multitenant control environment hosting your data.</span>"},{"id":"D6-079","domain":6,"obj":"6.4","diff":"medium","q":"A partner and an enterprise agree to jointly own and manage the risk of a shared cloud data-exchange platform, splitting responsibility and any losses between them. Which risk treatment does this describe?","options":["Risk acceptance","Risk avoidance","Risk sharing","Risk transfer"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Risk sharing</strong> — distributing responsibility and potential loss across multiple parties who jointly own the risk is risk sharing.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk acceptance</b>: acceptance means one party retains the risk without splitting it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk avoidance</b>: avoidance means not undertaking the shared platform at all.</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk transfer</b>: transfer moves the risk entirely to another party (e.g., insurer) rather than co-owning it.</span>"},{"id":"D6-080","domain":6,"obj":"6.5","diff":"medium","q":"A company wants its cloud contract to require the provider to carry its own cyber-insurance so that losses from a provider-caused breach are more likely to be recoverable. Which contract element supports this?","options":["A force majeure clause","A data classification clause","A capacity management clause","A cyber-insurance requirement clause"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>A cyber-insurance requirement clause</strong> — contractually requiring the provider to maintain adequate cyber-insurance improves the customer's ability to recover losses from a provider-caused incident.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A force majeure clause</b>: force majeure excuses performance during extraordinary events, not loss recovery.</span><span class='qd'><b>A data classification clause</b>: classification governs how data is labeled and handled, not insurance.</span><span class='qd'><b>A capacity management clause</b>: capacity management concerns resource scaling, not financial recovery.</span>"},{"id":"D6-081","domain":6,"obj":"6.4","diff":"hard","q":"A cloud risk assessment estimates that a control reduces annualized loss expectancy by $180,000 per year, while the control costs $220,000 per year to operate. Applying cost-benefit reasoning, what should the risk owner most likely conclude?","options":["The control's cost exceeds its benefit; consider accepting or a cheaper alternative","Implement the control because it reduces loss","Transfer the risk via the control","The control is mandatory regardless of cost"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The control's cost exceeds its benefit; consider accepting or a cheaper alternative</strong> — spending $220,000 to avoid $180,000 of expected annual loss is not cost-justified, so the owner should reconsider treatment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Implement the control because it reduces loss</b>: reducing loss is not sufficient if the control costs more than the benefit it delivers.</span><span class='qd'><b>Transfer the risk via the control</b>: a control mitigates rather than transfers risk, and this reasoning ignores the negative cost-benefit.</span><span class='qd'><b>The control is mandatory regardless of cost</b>: nothing indicates a legal mandate forcing an uneconomical control.</span>"},{"id":"D6-082","domain":6,"obj":"6.5","diff":"medium","q":"An organization wants to reduce lock-in risk before signing with a SaaS provider by ensuring it can retrieve its data in open, non-proprietary formats at any time. Which contractual provision best supports this?","options":["Limitation-of-liability clause","Data portability and format clause","Indemnification clause","Force majeure clause"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Data portability and format clause</strong> — guaranteeing retrieval of data in open, non-proprietary formats directly reduces lock-in and supports future migration.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Limitation-of-liability clause</b>: this caps damages and does nothing for data portability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Indemnification clause</b>: indemnification allocates liability for claims, not data export format.</span><span class='qd'><b>Force majeure clause</b>: force majeure addresses excused performance, not portability.</span>"},{"id":"D6-083","domain":6,"obj":"6.4","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the most complete list of the commonly recognized risk treatment options in enterprise risk management?","options":["Encrypt, log, monitor, patch","Detect, respond, recover, report","Avoid, mitigate, transfer, accept (and share)","Classify, label, retain, destroy"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Avoid, mitigate, transfer, accept (and share)</strong> — these are the standard risk treatment options an organization selects from when responding to identified risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Encrypt, log, monitor, patch</b>: these are specific technical controls, not risk treatment categories.</span><span class='qd'><b>Detect, respond, recover, report</b>: these describe incident-handling phases, not risk treatments.</span><span class='qd'><b>Classify, label, retain, destroy</b>: these are data-lifecycle activities, not risk treatments.</span>"},{"id":"D6-084","domain":6,"obj":"6.5","diff":"hard","q":"A cloud customer discovers its provider's right-to-audit clause is limited to reviewing published attestation reports and forbids independent penetration testing of the shared environment. From the customer's risk perspective, what is the most accurate characterization of this arrangement?","options":["It fully eliminates the need for the customer's own risk assessment","It is illegal under all cloud contracts","It converts the provider into the data controller","It is a restriction on audit scope the customer must weigh as residual assurance risk"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>It is a restriction on audit scope the customer must weigh as residual assurance risk</strong> — scope-limited audit rights are common with multitenant providers, and the customer must account for the reduced direct assurance as residual risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It fully eliminates the need for the customer's own risk assessment</b>: relying only on provider reports does not remove the customer's accountability to assess risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>It is illegal under all cloud contracts</b>: scope restrictions are standard and lawful, not illegal.</span><span class='qd'><b>It converts the provider into the data controller</b>: audit-scope terms do not change privacy-law roles.</span>"},{"id":"D6-085","domain":6,"obj":"6.4","diff":"medium","q":"An enterprise risk lead wants to understand the total risk exposure of a cloud service before considering any controls, to prioritize where controls are most needed. Which measure is she seeking?","options":["Inherent risk","Residual risk","Accepted risk","Transferred risk"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Inherent risk</strong> — the level of risk present before any controls are applied is inherent risk, useful for prioritizing where controls add the most value.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Residual risk</b>: residual risk is what remains after controls, not the pre-control baseline she wants.</span><span class='qd'><b>Accepted risk</b>: accepted risk is a treatment decision, not a pre-control exposure measure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Transferred risk</b>: transferred risk has been shifted to a third party, not the baseline exposure.</span>"},{"id":"D6-086","domain":6,"obj":"6.5","diff":"medium","q":"A CCSP is reviewing a proposed cloud SLA and notices it defines availability but never states how availability is measured, over what window, or what counts as downtime. What is the primary risk of accepting this SLA as written?","options":["The provider will owe excessive credits","Ambiguous metrics make the commitment unenforceable and disputes likely","It automatically voids the MSA","It forces the customer to become the data processor"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Ambiguous metrics make the commitment unenforceable and disputes likely</strong> — without defined measurement method, window, and downtime criteria, the availability target cannot be objectively enforced and will breed disputes.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The provider will owe excessive credits</b>: ambiguity typically favors the provider, not excessive customer credits.</span><span class='qd'><b>It automatically voids the MSA</b>: a vague SLA does not nullify the master agreement.</span><span class='qd'><b>It forces the customer to become the data processor</b>: SLA wording does not reassign privacy-law roles.</span>"},{"id":"D6-087","domain":6,"obj":"6.4","diff":"hard","q":"A global enterprise operates in regions with conflicting data-localization and disclosure laws, so a single cloud configuration cannot satisfy every jurisdiction at once. Which enterprise-risk activity best positions leadership to make defensible decisions here?","options":["Immediately accept all jurisdictional risk","Transfer all risk to the cloud provider","Assess the risk environment across jurisdictions and align treatment with risk appetite","Avoid the cloud entirely for all workloads"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Assess the risk environment across jurisdictions and align treatment with risk appetite</strong> — mapping conflicting legal obligations and choosing treatments consistent with a defined appetite gives leadership a defensible, documented basis for decisions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Immediately accept all jurisdictional risk</b>: blanket acceptance without analysis is not defensible governance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Transfer all risk to the cloud provider</b>: legal accountability for compliance cannot simply be transferred to the provider.</span><span class='qd'><b>Avoid the cloud entirely for all workloads</b>: total avoidance is disproportionate and ignores workloads with no conflict.</span>"},{"id":"D6-088","domain":6,"obj":"6.5","diff":"medium","q":"A company managing dozens of cloud vendors wants an ongoing program to onboard, monitor, reassess, and offboard suppliers based on their risk. What is this discipline called?","options":["Configuration management","Capacity management","Change management","Vendor (third-party) risk management"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Vendor (third-party) risk management</strong> — a structured lifecycle program to onboard, continuously monitor, reassess, and offboard suppliers by risk is third-party/vendor risk management.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Configuration management</b>: configuration management tracks system configuration items, not supplier relationships.</span><span class='qd'><b>Capacity management</b>: capacity management ensures adequate resource capacity, unrelated to vendor risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Change management</b>: change management governs controlled changes to systems, not vendor lifecycles.</span>"},{"id":"D6-089","domain":6,"obj":"6.4","diff":"medium","q":"A privacy officer distinguishes between data that is protected only because a contract says so versus data protected by statute. A dataset of PHI in a healthcare cloud falls into which category?","options":["Regulated (statutorily protected) private data","Contractually protected private data only","Public data","Anonymized data"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Regulated (statutorily protected) private data</strong> — PHI is protected by law (e.g., HIPAA), making it regulated private data with statutory obligations beyond any contract.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Contractually protected private data only</b>: contractual protection is only for data not otherwise covered by statute; PHI is statutorily covered.</span><span class='qd'><b>Public data</b>: PHI is sensitive personal health data, not public.</span><span class='qd'><b>Anonymized data</b>: PHI identifies individuals and is not anonymized.</span>"},{"id":"D6-090","domain":6,"obj":"6.5","diff":"hard","q":"During contract renewal, a provider proposes removing the customer's ability to obtain updated SOC 2 reports and to receive breach notifications within a defined time. From a compliance and risk standpoint, why should the customer resist?","options":["These clauses are purely cosmetic","They provide ongoing assurance and support the customer's own regulatory transparency duties","They benefit only the provider","They convert the SLA into an MSA"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>They provide ongoing assurance and support the customer's own regulatory transparency duties</strong> — continued access to SOC 2 reports and timely breach notice let the customer maintain assurance and meet its own legal breach-disclosure obligations, so removing them raises real risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>These clauses are purely cosmetic</b>: they materially affect the customer's assurance and compliance posture.</span><span class='qd'><b>They benefit only the provider</b>: the clauses primarily protect the customer, which is why the customer should keep them.</span><span class='qd'><b>They convert the SLA into an MSA</b>: these provisions do not change one document type into another.</span>"},{"id":"D6-091","domain":6,"obj":"6.4","diff":"easy","q":"Which statement best describes the relationship between a data owner/controller and a data custodian/processor in a cloud context?","options":["The custodian/processor is legally accountable for the data","They are always the same entity","The owner/controller is accountable while the custodian/processor handles operational care","The regulator acts as the custodian"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The owner/controller is accountable while the custodian/processor handles operational care</strong> — accountability rests with the owner/controller, while the custodian/processor carries out day-to-day handling under instruction.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The custodian/processor is legally accountable for the data</b>: accountability stays with the owner/controller, not the custodian/processor.</span><span class='qd'><b>They are always the same entity</b>: in cloud they are usually different parties (customer vs provider).</span><span class='qd'><b>The regulator acts as the custodian</b>: the regulator enforces law and does not act as custodian.</span>"},{"id":"D6-092","domain":6,"obj":"6.5","diff":"medium","q":"An organization wants contractual assurance that if the cloud provider suffers a security incident affecting the customer's data, the provider must notify the customer promptly with specified details. Which clause should be included?","options":["Force majeure clause","IP assignment clause","Capacity clause","Breach notification clause"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Breach notification clause</strong> — this clause obligates the provider to notify the customer within a defined timeframe with required details when an incident affects the customer's data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Force majeure clause</b>: force majeure excuses performance during extraordinary events, not incident reporting.</span><span class='qd'><b>IP assignment clause</b>: IP assignment addresses intellectual-property ownership, not breach notice.</span><span class='qd'><b>Capacity clause</b>: a capacity clause governs resource provisioning, not security-incident communication.</span>"},{"id":"D6-093","domain":6,"obj":"6.4","diff":"medium","q":"Leadership wants each cloud risk decision to be made by someone with the authority to accept the residual risk on the organization's behalf. Who should formally sign off on residual risk acceptance?","options":["The designated risk owner / accountable executive","The cloud provider's account manager","The penetration testing vendor","Any available system administrator"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The designated risk owner / accountable executive</strong> — residual risk must be accepted by the person with authority and accountability for the affected business function.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The cloud provider's account manager</b>: the provider cannot accept the customer's residual risk on its behalf.</span><span class='qd'><b>The penetration testing vendor</b>: testers identify weaknesses but have no authority to accept business risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Any available system administrator</b>: administrators lack the authority to accept enterprise risk.</span>"},{"id":"D6-094","domain":6,"obj":"6.5","diff":"hard","q":"A customer wants to ensure that a cloud provider's key security obligations survive even if the main contract term ends—for example, duties to protect and return data during wind-down. Which drafting concept accomplishes this?","options":["A force majeure carve-out","A survival clause specifying obligations that persist after termination","An exclusivity clause","A most-favored-customer clause"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A survival clause specifying obligations that persist after termination</strong> — survival clauses expressly keep designated obligations (data protection, return, confidentiality) in force after the contract ends.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A force majeure carve-out</b>: force majeure addresses excused non-performance, not post-termination obligations.</span><span class='qd'><b>An exclusivity clause</b>: exclusivity restricts dealing with competitors, unrelated to surviving duties.</span><span class='qd'><b>A most-favored-customer clause</b>: this guarantees best pricing terms, not post-termination security duties.</span>"},{"id":"D6-095","domain":6,"obj":"6.4","diff":"medium","q":"A CCSP advises that before selecting a risk treatment, the organization must ensure the chosen response does not push the residual risk above what leadership is willing to tolerate. Which concept is being referenced?","options":["Chain of custody","Data dispersion","Risk appetite/tolerance","Service credit"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Risk appetite/tolerance</strong> — the amount and type of risk leadership is willing to accept is the risk appetite/tolerance, which any treatment decision must respect.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Chain of custody</b>: chain of custody is a forensic evidence concept, not a risk-tolerance measure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data dispersion</b>: data dispersion is a storage technique spreading data across locations.</span><span class='qd'><b>Service credit</b>: a service credit is an SLA remedy, not a risk-tolerance concept.</span>"},{"id":"D6-096","domain":6,"obj":"6.5","diff":"easy","q":"Which agreement is specifically required under HIPAA between a covered entity and a cloud provider that will handle protected health information?","options":["Master Services Agreement (MSA)","Statement of Work (SOW)","Non-Disclosure Agreement (NDA)","Business Associate Agreement (BAA)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Business Associate Agreement (BAA)</strong> — HIPAA requires a BAA obligating the cloud provider (business associate) to safeguard PHI on the covered entity's behalf.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Master Services Agreement (MSA)</b>: an MSA sets general commercial terms but is not the HIPAA-mandated PHI safeguard agreement.</span><span class='qd'><b>Statement of Work (SOW)</b>: an SOW scopes project deliverables, not HIPAA obligations.</span><span class='qd'><b>Non-Disclosure Agreement (NDA)</b>: an NDA covers confidentiality generally but does not satisfy HIPAA's specific requirements.</span>"},{"id":"D6-097","domain":6,"obj":"6.4","diff":"hard","q":"A board asks why the organization still needs an internal cloud risk program when it has selected a highly certified provider. What is the most accurate justification a CCSP should give?","options":["Provider certifications cover the provider's controls, but the customer retains residual risk and accountability under shared responsibility","The certifications transfer all risk to the provider","Once certified, the provider becomes the data controller","Certifications eliminate the need for risk metrics"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Provider certifications cover the provider's controls, but the customer retains residual risk and accountability under shared responsibility</strong> — certifications attest to provider-side controls only; customer-side responsibilities and legal accountability remain, so an internal program is still required.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The certifications transfer all risk to the provider</b>: certifications are assurance evidence, not a transfer of risk or accountability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Once certified, the provider becomes the data controller</b>: certification does not change privacy-law roles.</span><span class='qd'><b>Certifications eliminate the need for risk metrics</b>: the organization still needs metrics to monitor its own posture.</span>"},{"id":"D6-098","domain":6,"obj":"6.5","diff":"medium","q":"A customer wants to prevent a provider from disclaiming virtually all responsibility for data loss by inserting an extremely low liability cap. Which negotiation focus most directly addresses this concern?","options":["Force majeure scope","Limitation-of-liability terms","Data classification labels","Capacity thresholds"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Limitation-of-liability terms</strong> — negotiating the liability cap (and carve-outs for data breaches) determines how much the provider can be held financially responsible for data loss.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Force majeure scope</b>: force majeure defines excused events, not the monetary liability cap.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data classification labels</b>: labeling controls handling of data, not liability allocation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Capacity thresholds</b>: capacity terms concern resource scaling, not financial responsibility.</span>"},{"id":"D6-099","domain":6,"obj":"6.4","diff":"medium","q":"An enterprise risk register lists a cloud misconfiguration risk as 'mitigated' after enabling automated configuration scanning and alerting. Which risk treatment was applied?","options":["Risk transfer","Risk avoidance","Risk mitigation","Risk acceptance"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Risk mitigation</strong> — adding controls such as automated configuration scanning and alerting to reduce likelihood or impact is risk mitigation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk transfer</b>: no third party is assuming the financial consequences here.</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk avoidance</b>: the activity continues, so the risk is not avoided.</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk acceptance</b>: acceptance would mean taking no action, but controls were added.</span>"},{"id":"D6-100","domain":6,"obj":"6.5","diff":"hard","q":"A customer's contract lets the provider unilaterally change subprocessors without notice. A downstream subprocessor is later breached, exposing the customer's data. Which combined weakness does this scenario best illustrate?","options":["Excessive service credits and force majeure abuse","Overly strict right-to-audit terms","Excessive data portability rights","Weak supply-chain governance and lack of subprocessor transparency"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Weak supply-chain governance and lack of subprocessor transparency</strong> — allowing silent subprocessor changes removes the customer's ability to assess fourth-party risk, exemplifying weak supply-chain governance and poor transparency.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Excessive service credits and force majeure abuse</b>: neither credits nor force majeure caused the unmonitored subprocessor exposure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Overly strict right-to-audit terms</b>: the problem is too little oversight, not overly strict audit rights.</span><span class='qd'><b>Excessive data portability rights</b>: strong portability would help the customer, not cause this breach.</span>"}]);
